The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are stamped as witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to belong to the older generation, they don't find work - for example, for health reasons, they're single and have no children.
If one of these women becomes a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot be dangerous to the rest of the village.
“Men are rarely affected by this fate.”
“Even young and healthy women keep this spared as they help work and give birth to children,” a sister describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso in a special home of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he issued a brochure that is meant to stop "witch persecution".
But the thing has a hook.
“More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” the newspaper pointed to the dilemma of written enlightenment.
But the accusation of witchcraft is also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, the 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured over her with oil and simply lit her on.
The incident was reported, among other things, by the BBC server.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the matter had only been a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, oil is flaming, which is used for ritual anointments.
And that after the group tried to "draw out" a "evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports people here regardless of their education.
"The Standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso as saying, "Friends of human souls are a danger earlier than today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to disarm the witch hunt, last year the Gambian president himself mixed well.
“President Yahya Jammeh sparked a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt’s death, as they allegedly had a share in their deaths and would now attempt to kill the president himself by black magic.”
“He called for help shamans from near-Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the President’s bodyguard, violently kidnapped women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the President’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, imprisoned people were forced to drink an absud of plants with hallucinogenic effect, which also caused bowel and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay at the farm.
It was only due to international pressure that nearly a thousand prisoners were released.
