The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with all that includes: colorful walls, creative furniture, lots of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from whose workshops comes a whole series of well-known Brno buildings, counted from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building with the premises for its company mini garden.
In wise prospects, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is committed to ensuring that the projectors return to their workplace as quickly as possible.
Along with the ability to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of its social program.
Civil engineers and architects have easier to put their demanding profession and child care under a hat.
The mini kindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini kindergarten is financed through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidy of CZK 2.8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment were obtained and for the duration of 2 years are provided for qualified personnel and operations.
After the funding has been exhausted (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini kindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company providing active assistance in the processing of the application.
The children care full-day qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can attend children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but several children alternate each other's day.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is about individual education and care, the program content in the mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
The children are not only playing here, they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus eliminate the stress of late picking up the children from a remote kindergarten.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also developing here.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and encourage their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric ax, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are ripped fish piles.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic shapes was nicknamed "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splitters and mosaics, the façades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dream lines, tender colours and textures that remind nature and living beings.
Only with a closer look can you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colours.
The same swinging lines and swallowed shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, ornamental elements of doors, even eye holes and bars.
The Batlló house in the Eixample neighborhood on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Gràcia No. 43 was built by the renovation of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of an entirely new building, but ultimately he agreed with Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
The rental house Casa Batlló, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the reality owner’s representative apartment and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also collaborated on the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Thus, Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí’s house Casa Milá in the Park Güell, which also includes other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "swinging house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique to the time with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Somewhat bizarre is her 45-degree inclination.
During his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be stuck by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city fathers were so terrified by the result that they demanded remedy.
The Councillors also encountered, among other things, that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, quite the opposite - only fifteen days after the request of the district in this regard, Josep Batlló submitted an application for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was granted to him promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a corporate lounge, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion removed all right angles and straight lines and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could conveniently chat without having to give up some intimacy during more confidential conversations.
The house received a fairly unusual roof and two more floors by Gaudí’s renovation in addition to a new facade.
Impressive is also Gaudí’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courts.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors that, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The House Casa Batlló, which was listed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this is a rather profitable business, the visits were retained, and they were also extended to further common and attic rooms, including the rooftop terrace.
The price for visiting the monument, however, is not a cardboard piece, it is 16.50 euros, students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders receive 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance rates for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friendship with one of the householders and visit him at home.
