More and more parents want human monitoring devices to keep the kids under control
The fear of their own children is growing, so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to search for cars, is as well able to locate people, which would also be helpful in such cases as recently in the traceless disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about as large as a cigarette box, but it is not likely to be larger than a wristwatch soon.
Many people have turned the case of the disappeared Anička into fear and fright, thus looking for ways to better protect their children.
Also for the price of impairment of their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying at all, but rather an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy,” said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices in the Czech market.
“I admit that there can be misuse of such equipment in individual cases, for example if you put it in someone’s pocket without them knowing it, but we haven’t had to record such a case so far.”
“Most customers really buy it for security reasons,” Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn’t like to wear such a thing, it simply gets rid of it.
“Even very small children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they don’t want to be controlled.”
"Initially, the cell phones raised great expectations from parents, but they can be turned off just as easily as these new monitoring devices," says Bočková.
In their view, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In planned kidnappings, the kidnapper practically always checks whether the child has any electronics with him to locate it."
"Today it's the cell phone."
