A longer pointing finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This is due to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty,” said the study’s co-author, Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health stresses, Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the right hand finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the likelihood of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of men whose ring and pointing fingers were equal.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already formed in the prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer pointing finger.
Earlier research has shown that just testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that this study was fleetingly known to him, but he does not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "completely proven".
