Overcrowded polls, multiple votes, voting bills in the stone, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were only part of the problems.
Election rooms opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless due to the January earthquake, struggled around in search of a choice.
Some finally gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded the cancellation of election results due to an alleged fraud.
There were partial violent protests throughout the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as “fairly good in many matters.”
According to a cautious statement by observers of the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, “these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process.”
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, allegedly committed to the unpopular departing President René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the provisional results on December 7.
The expected target election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial suit for invalidity.
If Jude Célestin, who finds little or no approval among the voters, declares the voter to be the winner of the election, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million earthquake victims still live in tents, low electoral participation was feared.
On the day of the election, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to lack of organization.
Just before the start of the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election were not yet issued.
There's a lot at stake.
Donor countries see a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves are of the same opinion.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following the sudden death of her husband, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, which is the highest value since her election in 2007.
However, whether this will help her to be re-elected next year depends on whether the apparently mourning Cristina Fernández is more compromised than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs of this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who led economic policy even after his wife’s election, often set up budgets that did not fully take into account tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential pair to spend the extra revenue in their own opinion.
On the paper, the Fernández government lost a majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided and Kirchner’s death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further crushes.
Some regime critics from the ranks of ruling Peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic meetings (in which one parliamentarian hit another and others accused the government of bribery), Congress failed to adopt the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to discuss it,” the president said.
The 2010 budget now applies to next year, giving the President even more opportunity to spend money in her own opinion.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is 11.1% at the time, but numerous private estimates - and wage demands from trade unions - drive the value to nearly 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction to be his main goals, not inflation reduction.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector and cleaned up the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently enhanced official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
She called on the private sector and the trade union leaders to talk.
And official statements say wage increases are expected to be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina’s agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
However, inflation undermined the growth boost due to a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina financially with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government entered into an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country’s previous redemption in 2001.
Now, Fernández seems to push for an agreement with the donors from the Paris Club, to whom she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as usual elsewhere.
But last month, Economic Minister Amado Boudou announced that the fund will provide "technical support" in the creation of a new national consumer price index, which appears to be the first step towards cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active even without the support of her husband after the end of her term.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which has largely enough of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentinians return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy that was brought to her will be depleted.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to quietly lift many of her husband’s political decisions.
