Arsenal-resistant microbe could enable new forms of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien species of bacteria that can live from arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
“This organism has two options.”
"He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
“That makes it very special, although it’s almost a sort of ‘strange’ lifestyle,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online issue of the journal Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, as the scientists found, the bacterium in Mono Lake in California grows even further, even if it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“There’s a question of what else is possible,” said the report’s co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms in other planetary systems can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements' that we think are absolutely vital to life are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Milton Keynes Open University in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not random.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose the Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes that are exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of Arsenal is primarily due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
“This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another.”
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus, it enters our biochemical system where it lubricates almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increased arsenic concentration, which adjusted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, it shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there has not been a working example yet.
Arsen was more common in the early earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
“That gives reason to believe that life may have also developed differently than in the early Earth Age,” said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
