“The good news is, the dogs are well,” Whitmore said.
“They are in good condition.”
"They were returned to their legitimate owners."
Whitmore did not give any accurate details of the dogs’ findings or the circumstances that led to their discovery.
“The investigation is still ongoing.”
“We don’t want to say more about it,” Whitmore explains.
“We’re following some traces.”
The dog owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were not available on Thursday for information.
They took their two dogs on Wednesday afternoon at a district animal shelter in Downey.
Sheriff officials found the van and the two dogs at different locations in Compton.
The Akitas - Trace, a 3-year-old goat, and Didi, a 10-month-old bitch - were uninjured, according to the official statement.
But the Corgis Bunny and Peter, who wanted to introduce Rickard and Peek to the competition this week on behalf of their Japanese owners, remained missing until Wednesday evening.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in the city this weekend because of the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach because Trace was scheduled to take part in the competition.
