The lion roars again after court approval of MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got green light for a new start.
A New York bankrupt judge on Thursday officially blessed the "prepared" crooks' plan to pay off the $5 billion debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company for new movies and TV shows.
According to Thursday’s statements, the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy law, so that the reboot of MGM under the leadership of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment, is no longer in the way.
The number of employees is reduced from over 400 to about 320.
For MGM, Chapter 11 is not effective until JPMorgan Chase has completed a planned $500 million bond to finance the new MGM productions.
Currently, a consortium of the investment bank, which itself makes $75 million, is running the company, and the financing is expected to last until mid-December.
The restructuring of the studio began in May 2009 with an order to investment bank Moelis & Co, the management of the company, which struggled with interest payments of $300 million/year to help solve their financial problems.
In August, Managing Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO at Enron and restructuring expert known for his activities at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper’s efforts to solve the financial concerns of MGMs and pay for the studio’s more than 140 fans took longer than expected.
After months of discussion, the parties decided to offer the company to buy at the end of 2009.
But the auction attracted few bidders and no one wanted to pay the $2 billion required by the creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything started from the start when the MGM team began the restructuring plan, which was finally signed by the creditors after months of debates and internal disputes at the end of October.
If MGM has officially survived the bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a bonus of several million dollars for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., which have already received $1.2 million, is $9.5 million.
Cooper, who was paid $375,000 monthly for running the company, will receive a "success bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM. This year, the studio released only one film and created an annual plan with seven or eight films to come to the cinemas in early 2012.
They also plan two films after "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
