The Ministry of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The verdict was a surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Ministry of Justice, and they believe that there was sufficient evidence that Ensign disregarded the lobbying ban.
Interviews, e-mails, and other documents first disclosed in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the presumption that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his electoral assistants, helped with lucrative orders to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as treasurer during the Ensigns election campaign.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton work, and according to the documents and interrogations, he took over the lobbying for them after recruiting Hampton.
As Hampton was recently in Ensign’s electoral team, he was not allowed to take on lobbying for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called ban on the turning door lobby.
According to the published evidence, "it seems to be an agreement and a breach of the rotary door statutes," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in the defense of clients targeted by the government.
While the Ministry of Justice officially refused to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethical lawyers said the Ministry seems very cautious in receiving political charges after a variety of defeats persecuted by the media with great interest, including the decision last year, to prosecute former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct.
Prosecutors “are obviously horrific,” said Melanie Sloan, chair of the Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington (a organization aimed at combating corruption in US parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers who brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to trial.
“This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them,” she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign’s chief defender, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another one the next day, notifying him that the ministry would not file a lawsuit against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defenders had cooperated with the prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to explain the legal arguments he had raised to the prosecutors in more detail.
"I don't feel comfortable going into the details of the talks between the Justice Department and me, just as much as it is said: we believe we made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to cease the investigation for a separate lawsuit by the ethics group, according to which a $96,000 payment from Mr. Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated the federal election law.
The electoral commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was anything else than a gift.
