Can courtesy connect the end?
Following a campaign of blasphemy and negativity, little politeness broke out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before we quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and Congressional leaders brought no breakthrough in the major issues to deal with during the so-called “lame duck session,” the meeting at the end of a rule that no longer made any decisions.
After all that you hear, it was not a polite discussion between two different sides or a consideration of their shared responsibility, but rather an empty episode of a partial point accumulation.
The public meeting of the President’s Deficit Commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that conceals the ideological gap that continues to separate members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one of the other demands willingness to cooperate and compromise, while one itself is trying to weigh down the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party warfare.
Thus, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of claims or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s about taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are kilometers away.
Lastly, the November election in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
In some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have hardly any choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to obtain some or even all, whether it is temporary or permanent.
Likewise, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favoured tax cuts for the wealthy while refusing support to unemployed workers.
After the White House meeting on Tuesday, optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratifie the New START Treaty.
However, William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session does not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what happens from today until 2012, as a preliminary fight, or shadow boxes, for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their formation.
No matter how worried the Republican leaders may be about pokering too high, they know they have to try to keep their promises to lower government spending and override health reform.
These party lines are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which involve a tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of retirement age and the reduction of government spending.
Vice-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pushed so much for putting the deficit issue on the public agenda that they can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling to get close to even that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for action or little sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when the Republicans challenge Obama with regard to the state budget, taxes, and the health system, later followed by a phase of bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It has been proven that, despite the partisanness of the current election, the majority of Americans still wish the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as it happened in 1995, both parties must carefully pay attention to public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change the course and seek the compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are now bigger than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
Thus, the courtesy that is being shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
However, it will require much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that continue to separate the two.
