Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a weakly illuminated, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminds the man who built it of the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years old.
Due to his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule known as "the slaughterer", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge high quarter in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrender to the government, longstanding followers in Anlong Veng are challenged.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed victims public confrontation with the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a school book that for the first time tells children of former soldiers the story of the Khmer Rouge.
And in July, a community court of the UN and Cambodia condemned for the first time a former Khmer Rouge member when it sentenced the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng Torture Chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among the Khmer Rouge veterans Alnlong Vengs, making their efforts to reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodia’s society more difficult.
“There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia’s documentation center, an independent organization that is exploring the regime.
“For her, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“It divides families themselves.”
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died from illness, overhaul or hunger.
When the Vietnamese invaded and the Pol Pot-Ied government collapsed in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the border of Cambodia to Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement surrendered.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their base west of the mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok drew up the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to move over to government, leading to the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who did not give up, was arrested by government forces at the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in the prison of Phnom Penh, where he was waiting for his trial.
As their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled into the depleting poverty of rural Cambodia and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Even though a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the simple soldiers remained poor, untrained peasants.
“These people have benefited very little from surrendering,” said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling down in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
“But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves.”
The current Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court will try to bring Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, to court.
The task of the court is to condemn the ancient leaders and those who are primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has helped little to alleviate the fears of Anlong Veng.
Current media speculations have focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials of Cambodia’s documentation center that she led the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that presumably killed thousands of forced workers.
On a hot evening, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty street outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past at the Khmer Rouge.
If the court invited her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
“If there were no more persecutions, there would be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court would charge more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
"Cambodia has to dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confrontation with the past is what Cambodia has to do to move forward, Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center said.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer times means gathering the broken pieces," he said.
“It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that they can understand everything.”
The centre created the first government-approved schoolbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the history book for the Ministry of Education’s high school, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
How often in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s connections to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new school book helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he brought the book home to read it.
“My family rejects many parts of the book and the court,” he said.
“They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people will be convicted by the court.”
Such resistance makes the process of reconciliation complex and complicated, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the school book and the court gradually gain influence,” he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a powerful attraction here.
Above in the Dangrek mountains, a path overgrowed by shrubs and stretched with plastic waste leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a tire pile after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone seller on the roadside, said she didn’t know much about the man who was burned here.
"But he has a strong spirit and a lot of people here go to him to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day she wanted to go to Pol Pot's last resting place, where she will drop a bush of mature bananas - in the hope that he will bring her happiness.
