In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty in the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the arising debate about the case depicted comes from a team of the Real Madrid football club (who claims nobility and honor in his anthem and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) playing the main role, and from the drama by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history than a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is not explicitly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute bypass of rules; in fact, this approach is consistent with the statutes of sport, but seems to bypass its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the unjustified benefits of the opposing team by the offender.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand as false gambling or bypassing rule, because the bypass of the rule was not carried out in secret to avoid a penalty, but it should be as striking as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and accepted the penalty with joy.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders derived from the deliberate faults.
Here it should be emphasized that the rival was neither put into an unfavourable position nor were there any benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that their own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It’s also not a useful strategy for the next game, as the club doesn’t have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it's a long-term advantage, to a certain degree uncertain, as the team could also leave at some point. In addition, players with this procedure will receive a penalty and go into the second card cycle, where they leave with a card accumulation less than in the first cycle.
It is not so clear if this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not against the sports spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to make the most of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to bypass a penalty (that would actually be a clear case of rules bypass), they preferred to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between the invention and the regulation environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of the invention.
