The U.S. changes the rules for receiving a visa
The persons must present themselves for visa application before their conversation with the consulate at the service agencies; costs will be shortened waiting times in this way.
From 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the United States embassy and the consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must introduce themselves to the visa application offices (ASC) before they speak in the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall retain the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the conversation.
The new procedure has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will decrease, as it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment arrangement, processing of the visa application and the transportation service by which the document is handed over separately.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to talk to the consulate, they only have to imagine themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second date to talk to the consulate will remain there less time than before.
Those applying for a visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service fee.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
