Climate: how France makes its financial promises beautiful
A year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the rapidly settled financing promises (also called "fast start" or premature financing) that have been realized by the developing countries.
And the rough French speeches have already been uncovered.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, the developing countries have undertaken to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million a year).
On the occasion of the opening of the COP16, the EU has drawn all the registers to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start financing: a detailed action report of its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its actual value: developing countries and civil society would like to see it if all developed countries did the same at the same level of precision.
In 2010, the EU announced that it released 2.2 billion euros, leading it to the right path toward improving its commitment of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But when you look into detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional effort has been made without being to the detriment of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the right value they consider best.
For example, the European Commission has chosen itself as a benchmark for that of 2009: the international financing will be maintained, and will contribute 150 million for over three years as part of the "fast start" funding.
Other countries have chosen similar guidelines, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France was of the view that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no guidelines for the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
Specifically, the overall amount of French support for developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France claims to meet its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown in donations and loans.
There is no rule about this yet, and everyone chooses their computing mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 € borrowed as equivalent to 1 € donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to accept: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (frequently emission-restraining projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro collected as an equivalent of a donated euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be accounted for as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of one).
But France has nothing other than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% of 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) are 100% fulfilling their commitments with donations.
In other words, when the overwhelming majority of the European Union spends €1 on fulfilling their obligations, France only gives 10 cents and understood a comparable commitment.
Beautiful Hokuspokus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double dizziness: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in negotiations, since the developing countries do not allow themselves to be completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question in a relatively short period of time compared to the whole of climate discussions.
But there could be too much of the drops in the immense machinery of UNFCCC.
Let’s hope that this won’t be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its type of accounting for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balanced justice with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could push the discussions on the subject matter of the long-term financing forward (a different, decisive and currently discussed issue): one does not escape the question of the "responsibility" or the type of accounting of its loans.
France could change its position to be just as progressive with regard to disputes as it is with other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement of France's fast-start and its vision of "responsibility" as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
